properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rain and wind expected. A strengthening low pressure system that is forecast to track northeastward across northeastern Ontario will bring heavy rain and gusty winds to the region beginning tonight. Rainfall totals of 30 to 50 mm are possible by the time the rain changes to snow Sunday night. Strong south to southeasterly winds gusting to 70 km/h are also possible tonight. These winds should diminish for a few hours during the day on Sunday before shifting to very strong northwesterlies gusting up to 90 km/h late Sunday afternoon. Wind warnings may be issued as the event draws near. Strong wind gusts may toss lose objects or cause tree branches to break. Power outages may occur. The potential for strong wind gusts should end Monday afternoon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Strong winds of 90 gusting to 110 km/h from Saturday evening to Sunday morning. An intense Pacific low pressure system will move through Queen Charlotte Sound and land on the central coast on Sunday morning. As the system approaches this evening, strong southeasterly winds will develop affecting northern Vancouver Island and southern Haida Gwaii. By midnight these winds will move onto the central coast. After midnight, as the low moves through Queen Charlotte Sound, the winds will shift to southwesterly for northern Vancouver Island and the central coast. Sunday morning will see the low nearly on the central coast. Winds for Haida Gwaii will turn northeasterly as they ease, while strong westerly winds continue for northern Vancouver Island and southern central coast. The westerly winds will abate near noon on Sunday. ### High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
